               <desc>
                  <p type="site-data">
                     Tianning Monastery (Tianning Si 天宁寺) is located in Xicheng District, Beijing. Traditionally attributed to the Northern Wei Dynasty under Emperor Xiaowen, some scholars, including Wang Shiren, propose that the temple originated during the Tang Dynasty under the name Tianwangsi (Tianwang Si 天王寺), dedicated to Vaisravana. The temple later evolved into a major monastery, becoming a center of Buddhist practice. 
                     The monastery’s layout has undergone major changes over time. Initially aligned west-east, it was reoriented to face north-south during the Ming Dynasty, a configuration that remains today. The central axis begins at the Mountain Gate (Shanmen 山门), which bears the inscription "Tianning Monastery" and is crowned by a hard hill-style roof (<term ref="/keyword/k000147">ying shan 硬山</term>) with gray tubular tiles. Further beyond the gate lies the Xumidian Hall (Xumi Dian 须弥殿), a key structure spanning five bays in width and three bays in depth, raised on a platform and flanked by the eastern and western halls. 
                     At the heart of the monastery stands the Tianning Pagoda (Tianning Si Ta 天宁寺塔), an octagonal, dense-eaves pagoda (mi yan shi 密檐式) built during the Tianqing reign of the Liao Dynasty in 1120. The pagoda features a multi-tiered design with eaves supported by bracket systems (<term ref="/keyword/k000019">dougong 斗拱</term>). Its intricate carvings (fudiao 浮雕) of Buddha figures, floral motifs, and dragons exemplify Liao architectural craftsmanship, inspired by the Buddhist Avatamsaka Sutra. 
                     The monastery expanded under Emperor Yongle of the Ming Dynasty (r. 1402–1424), who renamed it Tianning Monastery in 1435 during the Xuande reign. Subsequent renovations took place during the Qianlong reign (1756) and in 1938. Designated a National Key Cultural Relic Protection Unit (Quanguo Zhongdian Wenwu Baohu Danwei 全国重点文物保护单位) in 1988, the Tianning Monastery continues to serve as an enduring symbol of Beijing’s Buddhist heritage and monastic tradition.   
                  </p>
